### Description
When I enable top-level await in Tyoescrpt. (setting module do `esnext`  and set target to `es2017` (or higher)  TS and JS support using top-level await. 

That means that this becomes valid:
```typescript
  const { BrowserModule } = await import('@angular/platform-browser');
  const { NgModule } = await import('@angular/core');

  const { AppRoutingModule } = await import('./app-routing.module');
  const { AppComponent } = await import('./app.component');
  const { HomeComponent } = await import('./home/home.component');
  const { HttpClientModule } = await import('@angular/common/http');

  @NgModule({
    declarations: [AppComponent, HomeComponent],
    imports: [BrowserModule, AppRoutingModule, HttpClientModule],
    providers: [],
    bootstrap: [AppComponent],
  })
  export class AppModule {}
```

This is now valid typescript, which translates into valid modules.
However, When I try to use this with the CLI, I'm facing a syntax error?
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1249083/109251988-c40b6380-77ec-11eb-96b6-c10e39139580.png)

This is not a syntax error from typescript. Where does it come from, and why is it there?

When this would work, it enables a way more fine-grained control over lazy-loading, and would cut down bundle-size in a huge way.


